<!--Race problematized, and overall "con's" of the concept:-->
While scientists use the concept of race to make practical distinctions among [[fuzzy set]]s of traits, the [[scientific community]] feels that the idea of race is often used by the general public<ref name = "Graves"/> in a naïve<ref name = "Lee-Mountain"/> or simplistic way, erroneously designating wholly discrete types of individuals. Among humans, race has no [[Cladistics|cladistic]] significance&mdash;all people belong to the same [[hominid]] subspecies, ''Homo sapiens sapiens''.<ref name=Keita2004>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1038/ng1455 |title=Conceptualizing human variation |year=2004 |last1=Keita |first1=S O Y |last2=Kittles |first2=R A |last3=Royal |first3=C D M |last4=Bonney |first4=G E |last5=Furbert-Harris |first5=P |last6=Dunston |first6=G M |last7=Rotimi |first7=C N |journal=Nature Genetics |volume=36 |pages=S17 |pmid=15507998 |issue=11 Suppl}}</ref><ref name="AAPA">[http://www.virginia.edu/woodson/courses/aas102%20(spring%2001)/articles/AAPA_race.pdf AAPA Statement on Biological Aspects of Race] American Association of Physical Anthropologists "Pure races, in the sense of genetically homogeneous populations, do not exist in the human species today, nor is there any evidence that they have ever existed in the past."</ref> Regardless of the extent to which race exists, the word "race" is problematic and may carry negative connotations.<ref name = "Brace">Brace CL (2000). [http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/first/brace.html ''Does race exist? An antagonist's perspective]''. Pbs.org. Retrieved 11 October, 2010.</ref> Social conceptions and [[racial grouping|groupings]] of races vary over time, involving [[folk taxonomy|folk taxonomies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.americanethnography.com/article.php?id=36 |title = The Concept of Race |last =  Montagu |first = Ashley |authorlink = Ashley Montagu |publisher = ''American Ethnography Quasimonthly'' |accessdate = 26 January 2009 |date = 2008 [1962]}}</ref><ref name="US_Brazil">For example, a person who in the [[United States]] would be called "Hispanic" or "African American" might be called "Branca" (white) in the racial categorization system commonly used in [[Brazil]].</ref><ref>Bamshad, Michael and Steve E. Olson. [http://schools.tdsb.on.ca/rhking/departments/science/bio/evol_pop_dyn/does_race_exist.pdf "Does Race Exist?"], ''Scientific American Magazine'' (10 November 2003).</ref> that define [[Wikt:essentiality|essential types]] of individuals based on perceived sets of traits. Scientists consider biological [[essentialism]] obsolete,<ref name = "Sober">Sober E (2000). ''Philosophy of biology'' (2nd ed.). Boulder, CO: Westview Press.</ref> and generally discourage racial explanations for collective differentiation in both physical and behavioral traits.<ref name = "Lee-Mountain">{{Cite journal|last1=Lee |first1=Sandra S. J. |last2=Mountain |first2=Joanna |first3=Barbara |last3=Koenig |first4=Russ |last4=Altman |first5=Melissa |last5=Brown |first6=Albert |last6=Camarillo |first7=Luca |last7=Cavalli-Sforza |first8=Mildred |last8=Cho |first9=Jennifer |last9=Eberhardt |year=2008 |title=The ethics of characterizing difference: guiding principles on using racial categories in human genetics|pages=404 |journal=Genome Biology |volume=9|pmid=18638359 |issue=7 |at=article 404|pmc=2530857 |url=http://genomebiology.com/2008/9/7/404 |accessdate=2 July 2010 |doi=10.1186/gb-2008-9-7-404 |quote=We caution against making the naive leap to a genetic explanation for group differences in complex traits, especially for human behavioral traits such as IQ scores }}</ref><ref>For example, the following statement expresses the official viewpoint of the [[American Anthropological Association]] at [http://www.aaanet.org/stmts/racepp.htm their web page]: "Evidence from the analysis of genetics (e.g., DNA) indicates that most physical variation, about 94%, lies within so-called racial groups. Conventional geographic "racial" groupings differ from one another only in about 6% of their genes. This means that there is greater variation within "racial" groups than between them."</ref>

<!--Race as constructed reality, and some consequences thereof-->
As people define and disseminate different conceptions of race, they actively create contrasting social realities through which racial categorization is achieved in varied ways.<ref name = "Lee_judicial">Lee JC (1997). "Review essay: Navigating the topology of race". In EN Gates (Ed.), ''Crititical Race Theory: Essays on the Social Construction and Reproduction of "Race"'' (Vol. 4, ''The Judicial Isolation of the "Racially" Oppressed'', pp. 393&ndash;426, p. 396. New York: Garland Publishing, Inc.</ref> In this sense, races are said to be [[social construct]]s.<ref name = "NRC">See, for example, National Research Council (2004). ''Measuring racial discrimination'' (Ch. 2). Washington: The National Academies Press.</ref><ref name = "Smaje">[[cf.]] Smaje C (1997). "Not just a social construct: Theorising race and ethnicity". ''Sociology(31)''2, pp. 307&ndash;327.</ref> These constructs can develop within various legal,<ref name = "Lee_judicial"/><ref name = "Harris"/> economic,<ref name = "Harris">Harris CI (1995). "Whiteness as property". In K Crenshaw; N Gotanda; G Peller; K Thomas (Eds.) ''Critical Race Theory: The Key Writings That Formed the Movement'' (pp. 276 &ndash;291), p. 287.</ref> and sociopolitical<ref name = "Morgan"/><ref name = "Nobles">Nobles M (2000). ''Shades of citizenship: Race and the census in modern politics'' (Ch. 4). Stanford, CA: Stanford University Press.</ref> contexts, and at times may be the effect, rather than the cause, of major social situations.<ref name = "Morgan">Morgan ES, cited in Lee (1997), p. 407.</ref> Socioecomonic factors,<ref name = "Morgan"/><ref name="SA_HistIdea"/><ref name = "Sivanandan">Sivanandan A, cited in Miles R (2000). "Apropos the idea of 'race' ... again". In L Black; J Solomos (Eds.), ''Theories of Race and Racism'' (pp. 125&ndash;143). London: Routledge.</ref><ref name = "Crenshaw">Crenshaw KW (1988). "Race, reform, and retrenchment: Transformation and legitimation in antidiscrimination law". ''Harvard Law Review(101)''7, pp. 1331&ndash;1337.</ref><ref name = "Conley">Conley D (2007). "Being black, living in the red". In PS Rothenberg (Ed.), ''Race, Class, and Gender in the United States'' (7th ed.), pp. 350&ndash;358. New York: Worth Publishers.</ref> in combination with early but enduring<ref name = "Winfield_quote">The notion of racial hierarchy has ancient origins: "It was [[Aristotle]] who first arranged all animals into a single, graded scale that placed humans at the top as the most perfect iteration. By the late 19th century, the idea that inequality was the basis of [[Natural order (philosophy)|natural order]], known as the ''[[great chain of being]]'', was part of the common [[lexicon]]." Winfield AG (2007). ''Eugenics and education in America: Institutionalized racism and the implications of history, ideology, and memory'' (pp. 45&ndash;46, emphasis in original). New York: Peter Lang Publishing, Inc.</ref> views of race, have led to considerable suffering amongst the disadvantaged racial groups. <!--Saved for potential future use, and also to retain citations: Historically, when racial distinctions have coincided with differential correlates of [[Power (communication)|social power]],<ref name = "Sivanandan">Sivanandan A, cited in Miles R (2000). "Apropos the idea of 'race' ... again". In L Black; J Solomos (Eds.), ''Theories of Race and Racism'' (pp. 125&ndash;143). London: Routledge.</ref> such as [[Social class|economic class]],<ref name = "Conley">Conley D (2007). "Being black, living in the red". In PS Rothenberg (Ed.), ''Race, Class, and Gender in the United States'' (7th ed.), pp. 350&ndash;358. New York: Worth Publishers.</ref> these distinctions have been adopted by the powerful [[hegemony]]<ref name = "Crenshaw">Crenshaw KW (1988). "Race, reform, and retrenchment: Transformation and legitimation in antidiscrimination law". ''Harvard Law Review(101)''7, pp. 1331&ndash;1337.</ref> as visual indicators<ref name = "Hirschfeld">Hirschfeld LA (1998). ''Race in the making: Cognition, culture, and the child's construction of human kinds'' (Ch. 6). Cambridge: Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</ref><ref name = "Levin">See also Levin D (2000). "Race as a visual feature: Using visual search and perceptual discrimination tasks to understand face categories and the cross-race recognition deficit". ''Journal of Experimental Psychology'': General, 129, pp. 559–574.</ref> of [[Out-group homogeneity bias|apparently homogeneous]] [[Outgroup (sociology)|outgroups]].<ref name = "Baumeister">Baumeister RF; Bushman BJ (2007). ''Social psychology and human nature'' (pp. 405&ndash;406). Belmont, CA: Thomson Higher Learning.</ref> When these divisions have served the intrests of the powerful, they have been amplified into [[Racism|racist]] attitudes accompanied by racial [[stereotype]]s, and have led to [[racial discrimination]]. Early<ref name = "Winfield_quote">The notion of racial hierarchy has ancient origins: "It was [[Aristotle]] who first arranged all animals into a single, graded scale that placed humans at the top as the most perfect iteration. By the late 19th century, the idea that inequality was the basis of [[Natural order (philosophy)|natural order]], known as the ''great chain of being'', was part of the common [[lexicon]]." Winfield AG (2007). ''Eugenics and education in America: Institutionalized racism and the implications of history, ideology, and memory'' (pp. 45&ndash;46). New York: Peter Lang Publishing, Inc.</ref> ideas of race have factored into many instances of tragedy,<ref name=KO_Genomic/> including [[slavery]] and [[genocide]].--> Scholars continue to debate the degrees to which racial categories are biologically warranted<ref name = "Brace"/><ref name = "Gill"/> and socially constructed, as well as the extent to which the realities<ref name = "Lee_quote">"The very naturalness of 'reality' is itself the effect of a particular set of discursive constructions. In this way, discourse does not simply refle